Date: Tue, 4 Aug 1998 09:43:44 +1200
From: Kitty Croxson <KittyC@ahsl.co.nz>

I note the possibility of ground water contamination in the Sydney water
supply. The Greater Victoria area, British Columbia, had a problem of
excess acute _Toxoplasma_ infections, documented by Bowie et al Lancet
1997;350:173-177, which was assumed to be ground water contamination of the
municipal water supply plus filter break-down. A massive screening program
for pregnant women was developed and 36 acute infections identified. I
wonder if the possibility of _Toxoplasma_ contamination and risk to
pregnant women has been considered in Sydney. I am a pathologist
(virologist) somewhat sensitized to _Toxoplasma_ infections in pregnancy
since our laboratory is responsible locally for _Toxoplasma_ serology and
PCR testing of amniotic fluid for _Toxoplasma_ DNA.
--
Kitty Croxson
e-mail: KittyC@ahsl.co.nz
[Having once been involved in the serological monitoring of some 1,700
pregnant women here in Baton Rouge, I would point out that such procedures
are not straightforward. Some pregnant women with prior & chronic
_Toxoplasma_ infections can suffer from the rupture of these cysts and a
resulting increase in titres, though the pregnancy may not be at risk. My
memory tells me that we had five such women and all were delivered of
normal infants. That is beside the point ... the question remains whether
the Sidney Public Health authorities have considered such a scenario as
described by Kitty Croxson. - Mod.MHJ
***
[The following is presented as a "once only and not to be repeated" lesson
in the complexities of municipal public health, real and perceived.
ProMED-mail is not a forum for lawyers and politics but we should be aware
