[2
Date: Mon, 03 Aug 1998 11:56:04 +1000
From: Stephen Murray <Stephen.Murray@parliament.nsw.gov.au>

I've noted the deletion of references to the "circling lawyers" in the
previous posting on this subject, but some attention needs to be paid to
them. A number of firms have taken to the media touting for business,
including the placement of advertisements in daily newspapers, seeking
participation in a class action against Sydney Water. One such
advertisement had a fill in and clip out coupon. The basis of the class
action would seem to be compensation for measures taken to avoid exposure
to giardia, such as the purchase of bottled water.
It would seem to me that any successful class action would have at least
two effects: (1) any damages payable by Sydney Water would merely be passed
on to consumers by way of increased water rates; and (2) while Sydney
Water's immediate response may be criticised, in the end it recommended the
broadest possible response to the situation, covering the entire Sydney
metropolitan area, not just those serviced by the affected station. Any
successful class action might have the effect of encouraging a minimal or
contained response in future, rather than the broadly applied measures seen
in this instance. I would be interested in any views on this matter.
Furthermore, a representative of one of the more aggressive law firms (I
know, it sounds tautologous, but believe me the qualifier is necessary) was
interviewed on a radio current affairs this morning (August 3, 1998) saying
that Sydney Water had to pay massive damages because this situation was
"unprecedented in the Western world". Can anyone assist in ascertaining the
veracity of this statement?
--
Stephen Murray
Research Assistant
Parliament House
Sydney Australia
e-mail: csmurray@parliament.nsw.gov.au

[3
Date: Sun, 02 Aug 1998 12:45:36 +1000
From: Mike Melville <M.Melville@unsw.edu.au>

In the past, Sydney Water Board assisted public anxiety about sewage
pollution to Sydney beaches as a precursor to a special tax that basically
enabled construction of very expensive engineering works for sewerage
ocean-outfalls.
I am sufficiently skeptical therefore, as to wonder whether the present
"crisis" about Sydney water precedes some new, very expensive, other
engineering works in the water treatment system; a move to resurrect the
Welcome Reef Dam/ Upper Shoalhaven River water supply for Sydney scheme; or
something to do with further privatisation of Sydney water supply. I
understand that the health service at our University has for a long time
and on a regular basis, been dealing with the presentation of giardiasis so
the issue is not really new. We can watch with interest as the crisis
develops in the media.
--
Dr M.D. Melville
School of Geography
University of New South Wales
e-mail: M.Melville@unsw.edu.au
